title: Grateful Dead Live at Boston Garden on 1994-10-03
lineage: Dat (Tascam DA-20) -> Tascam DA-3000 -> Samplitude Professional v11.2.1 -> FLAC/
description:
Set 1

Touch Of Gray-> Beat It On Down The Line, Loose Lucy, Little Red Rooster, Childhood's End, Dire Wolf, Black Throated Wind*, Bird Song

Set 2

Box Of Rain, Shakedown Street, Cassidy-> Goin' Down The Road Feelin' Bad-> Drums-> Space-> The Wheel-> All Along The Watchtower-> Attics Of My Life-> Around & Around, E: Brokedown Palace

* Weir on acoustic guitar

reviews.review_text:
Boston '94.... my last solidly consistent shows Saw 3 of the fall '94 run... 9/29, 10/1 and 10/3.  Had tickets for the whole run, but life was hectic as a 35 year old attorney and father of 2 young girls.... so I picked and chose based on schedule leaving me with these 3 shows....  other than the train wreck of an I Fought the Law encore on 9/29, I felt like I caught 3 solid shows.... nothing that so much as hinted at the Giants Stadium disaster from August 3rd, or forebode the crash and burn of 1995.....   
 or the train wrecks in DC a week later [4th row center the 3rd night at the US Air Arena fka Cap Center, and Jerry was a mess].... just solid tune selection and playing.... But that's the nature of smack.  A fine line between a euphoric high and being a total waste....   Anyway..... I enjoyed this one.... especially the pre-drumz section of 2nd set..... nice to see Cassidy and GDTRFB in those slots.....   Yes, there were some redeeming moments in 1994.... and as a native of north Jersey and a hater of the Bruins [GO RANGERS!!!], it still rings ironic that the old Boston Garden was the sight of my last good shows......   And my rating is based on a combination of music, song selection, playing, and how much effing fun I had at the show.... and truth be told, the latter bumped it a star!!

A Latter-Day Masterpiece! 1994 shows could be hit or miss. This one is a line drive home run! From the first tuneup and opening chords, the band and the crowd seem to recognize that Captain Trips is very much present and accounted for, and the boys take that realization and run with it. Phil has the volume cranked up nicely, and Kreutzmann rattles Touch of Grey into such a frenzy that they actually have to bring it down half a notch for Beat it on Down the Line, which is still a crisp little cooker. The song selection of the first set alone is brilliant, besides the fact that they played it so damn well. It being the closing night of a lengthy stand at the Boston Garden, it seems like they really made an effort to ask themselves "what songs haven't we played yet, and how can we keep this crowd on their toes?" The first set solution: rocker, rocker, rocker, blues standard, ballad, upbeat folk/country tune, ballad, brooding psychedelic jam vehicle. All played to fantastic effect! Bird Song is especially brilliant in a year that saw so many great ones.

A beautiful Box of Rain opens the second set, and they stretch Shakedown way out. Cassidy is marvelous, and GDTRFB, which at the time was a rarity, is peppered with rapid drumming and old school rock & roll guitar licks. Drums > Space really went some places in 1994, and this one saunters away into some murky, aquatic, sonar-like soundscapes before the beacon of Bob Weir's guitar flags it down and lassos it into reach of Garcia's shredding distortion. Bells and robotic birds add to the MIDI madness, and it sounds like it's about to churn into The Other One, but then Lightning Bolt gradually rises from the insanity with a pleasant, unhurried clarity that plucks the band from the depths and places them on The Wheel. Garcia's two American Beauty selections are the real gems of the second set, if not the whole show. From reading the reviews of actual attendees, even though he played brilliantly well this night it seems like a lot of fans and perhaps even Jerry himself knew that this would be his farewell to Massachusetts, making this wonderful post-Space segment even more special.

In a venue that hosted such legendary shows as 4/2/73, 5/7/77, 9/26/91, and 10/1/94, I think the Grateful Dead's final Boston Garden show on 10/3/94 truly has its own special nook in not only the venue's history, but the band's history. This Miller SBD just keeps following me around. I've listened to it all the way through 3 times in the last 5 months and it still amazes me every time. The balance is exquisite and there's a slight echo around the vocals that's almost like a May '77 Betty board. One or two different song selections might've spoiled this show, but the setlist is so beautifully crafted and performed that for me it gets an automatic 5 stars. They can never say Jerry Garcia didn't go out of the Boston Garden with a bang.

I am on an amazing journey I am listening to every 1994 show in order, mining for gold. 

This one is a winner. Great soundboard, setlist, and performance overall. Drums>Space is exceptional. The Grateful Dead of the '90s at its best. 

Set 1 highlights: Solid set, front to back.

Set 2 highlights: Box of Rain, Shakedown Street, second set Cassidy, GDTRFB!!!! Loved the post Space numbers as well. 

Boston Garden truly was a Brokedown Palace by this time. Great send off for the venue.
